				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>Ser54 corresponds to Ser35 in AmpR , Ser33 in OxyR , and Ser38 in CysB and GcvA , and these residues are required for DNA binding but not oligomerization ( 27 , 43 -- 45 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24659766" target="_blank">24659766</a>]<br></li>
<li>Their opposite promoters overlap in a way that is reminiscent of two other gene pairs that exhibit sRNA regulation by transcription factors , including oxyS control by OxyR in response to oxidative-stress , and GcvA regulating gcvB in response to glycine levels ( 6,39 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18267966" target="_blank">18267966</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mutational analysis of the transcriptional-regulator GcvA : amino acids important for activation , repression , and DNA binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24659766" target="_blank">24659766</a>]<br></li>
<li>Alternatively , glycine may serve as a regulatory molecule ( undulating line ) , disrupting the complex formed between GcvR-GcvA , freeing GcvA to activate transcription of the GcvB sRNA and thereby leading to posttranscriptional regulation of the GcvB regulon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26574511" target="_blank">26574511</a>]<br></li>
<li>The regulatory cascade leading to GcvB production is initiated when glycine disrupts the protein complex formed between GcvA and GcvR , freeing GcvA to activate transcription of gcvB and other target genes ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26574511" target="_blank">26574511</a>]<br></li>
